# Session log -- 2026-05-12

**Topic:** KPU derived TDP (V²·f power model) + self-describing SKU naming convention with cross-foundry comparison sweeps
**Branches landed on `main`:**
  - graphs PR #153 (squash commit `3549472`)
  - graphs PR #155 (squash commit `e8e2463`)
  - embodied-schemas PR #14 (squash commit `846a0d2`)
**Cross-repo:** yes — embodied-schemas (schema additions + 8 new SKU YAMLs + 4 legacy renames + 1 ProcessNode update) + graphs (power model module + naming-convention adoption everywhere)

## What we set out to do

The session opened with the user asking whether we had a utility to print a
ComputeProduct YAML hierarchy for a given KPU id. That spawned `cli/show_compute_product.py`, which composed the existing per-layer inspectors into one assembled view. Spotting the t256 PE-array discontinuity (20×20 vs the rest of the family at 32×32) during catalog inspection became the entry point for the much larger arc that landed today: deriving TDP from configuration, fixing t256's PE array, and adopting a self-describing SKU naming convention so the catalog reads as a comparison matrix.

Three arcs of design progression, each with a user-driven course correction:

1. **Arc 1 — t256 PE-array fix + PE-array programmability** (graphs PR #153
   first half). User asked to bump t256 from 20×20 to 32×32 (uniform with
   t64/t128) and to make PE-array size programmable so we can quickly
   generate roadmap sweeps. Shipped `apply_pe_array_override(spec, rows,
   cols)` that resizes every tile class and rescales `ops_per_tile_per_clock`
   by `new_pes/old_pes` to preserve per-PE op throughput. Surfaced as
   `--pe-array ROWSxCOLS` on `cli/generate_kpu_sku.py`. Roadmap sweep at
   fixed 256 tiles, 1.4 GHz: 16×16 → 183 TOPS / 124 mm², 32×32 → 734 TOPS
   / 188 mm², 40×40 → 1147 TOPS / 236 mm² — clean cost/perf curve.

2. **Arc 2 — derived TDP from V/f/workload** (graphs PR #153 second half +
   embodied-schemas PR #14 schema additions). User: "yes, derive TDP from
   configuration." First cut was a compute-only model with an
   `activity_factor` back-computed to make t256 land at 30W. Lined up within
   ~20% on t64/t128/t256 but undercounted t768 (datacenter, more
   memory-bound) by 56%. User picked the fuller model:
   "Add SRAM/NoC/DRAM energy terms." Schema gained
   `ProcessNodeEntry.{sram_access_pj_per_byte, dram_io_pj_per_byte,
   noc_pj_per_flit_per_hop}` and `KPUThermalProfile.{vdd_v, activity_factor}`.
   New `graphs.hardware.kpu_power_model` module ships a 5-term roll-up
   (PE compute + L2 + L3 + NoC + DRAM PHY + leakage) with V²·f scaling on
   all dynamic terms.

   The big course-correction was the user's question: "How do you get
   different profiles, such as 11.3/12.3/13.2 for the t64?" — pointing out
   that varying clock alone (within the catalog's narrow 850/900/950 MHz
   spread) only swings TDP by 12% when real chips like Orin span 3-5× via
   `V²·f`. Added per-profile `vdd_v` to the schema. Catalog regen for all
   4 legacy SKUs landed derived TDPs within ±0.5W of catalog targets, but
   required dropping clocks substantially (e.g., t256 default 1400 → 600
   MHz) — the prior catalog clocks were aspirational marketing numbers,
   not sustainable operating points. New clocks line up with real-world
   Orin AGX (420/624/828 MHz at 15/30/50W).

3. **Arc 3 — self-describing SKU naming convention** (embodied-schemas
   PR #14 + graphs PR #155). User wanted a strict comparison protocol where
   only one variable changes at a time, with the variable encoded in the
   SKU id so `list_kpus.py` reads as a comparison matrix. Three convention
   proposals presented (positional / compact-with-feature-tags / faceted-
   kebab); user picked the compact form. Refined across multiple rounds:

   - Tile count first (`t<N>` prefix): "tile count is the strongest top-
     level attribute"
   - Process node as `<value>nm` (matches industry usage)
   - Add foundry as separate segment to dodge cross-foundry collisions
     (`_12nm` alone is ambiguous between GF 12FDX, GF 12LP+, TSMC N12)
   - Always include library variant tag — even when not strictly needed
     for disambiguation today — because the library tag conveys product
     positioning (`fdx`/`ull` = energy-efficient FD-SOI, `hpc` = datacenter
     compute, `lpp`/`pp`/`ffp` = FinFET performance)

   Final convention: `kpu_t<count>_<rows>x<cols>_<mem><ch>_<value>nm_<foundry>_<library>`

   Test sweep at GF 12FDX (4 SKUs: t64/t128/t256/t512 with channels
   doubling 4/8/16/32) validated the convention. User: "create a 7nm tsmc
   sweep as well so we can see the first comparison." Mirror sweep at
   TSMC N7 HPC with identical architecture and operating points landed,
   producing the canonical cross-foundry comparison: 256-tile / 32×32 PE,
   600 MHz @ 0.65V — 12FDX gives 22W / 214 mm² / 315 TOPS while N7 HPC
   gives 10W / 59 mm² / 315 TOPS. **Same compute at half the power and
   3.6× smaller die** — exactly the process-node delta in isolation, which
   is what the comparison protocol is designed to surface.

   Three refinements during the convention adoption: dynamic column widths
   in `list_kpus.py` (the new SKU ids broke the hardcoded 30-char column);
   added `--foundry` / `--node-nm` / `--library` filter flags for query
   ergonomics; tier vocabulary expanded `entry < mid < high < datacenter`
   to `entry < mid < high < enthusiast < datacenter` so the t512 SKUs
   slot into the "enthusiast" bucket (Intel Core X / AMD Threadripper /
   NVIDIA RTX Spark prosumer positioning) rather than overloading the
   `model_tier` field with my initial `sweep_12fdx` placeholder string
   (which the user rightly flagged as carrying no good information).

After all three arcs, the user requested a full migration of the legacy
`stillwater_kpu_*` SKUs to the new convention. Mechanical rename touched 30+
files: 4 catalog YAMLs renamed (with internal `id` field updates), 8 source
files (factories, mappers, loader, validators), 5 test files
(parametrize lists), 3 `hardware_registry/` directories, 6 CLI tools' default
args/examples, 2 doc files. 680/680 hardware tests pass on the migrated
branch.

## Decisions

- **DECISION-2026-05-12-001** — Derived TDP from configuration with V²·f
  scaling and full memory-subsystem terms (chose option 2 from the fidelity
  question). Required schema extensions on `ProcessNodeEntry` (SRAM/NoC/DRAM
  per-byte / per-flit / per-byte energies) and on `KPUThermalProfile`
  (`vdd_v`, `activity_factor`). The compute-only quick-win and the annotate-
  alongside-existing-TDP options were rejected because they couldn't honor
  the user's downstream goal of a roadmap-honest cost/perf curve.

- **DECISION-2026-05-12-002** — Self-describing SKU naming convention adopted
  catalog-wide with full migration of legacy SKUs (chose
  `kpu_t<count>_<rows>x<cols>_<mem><ch>_<value>nm_<foundry>_<library>` over
  positional all-fields-explicit and faceted-kebab alternatives, then
  refined to add foundry-and-library segments). The "soft deprecation" and
  "annotate-only" options were rejected because the catalog is the source
  of truth and any consumer querying by SKU id needs the new convention to
  identify SKUs by their architecturally-distinguishing dimensions.

